1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,736
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:17,716 --> 00:00:34,816
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sammasambuddhassam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:35,337 --> 00:00:47,570
This evening I was just going to let my mind wander around the factors of enlightenment and dependent origination, just see where we go, you know.

4
00:00:48,968 --> 00:00:58,920
One of the things I've been stressing this week, in fact I tend to be stressing it a lot, is this quality of equanimity.

5
00:01:02,024 --> 00:01:05,868
And it seems to me that equanimity is twofold.

6
00:01:09,474 --> 00:01:16,022
Its ratings, just before I go into that, its rating in Buddhist virtues is the highest.

7
00:01:17,132 --> 00:01:20,317
There's a lovely book called Vision of the Dhamma by Jnana Ponica.

8
00:01:21,418 --> 00:01:22,420
He was a German monk.

9
00:01:22,501 --> 00:01:23,262
He's died now.

10
00:01:25,745 --> 00:01:37,621
And he points out that equanimity lies beneath any virtue and therefore is of enormous importance to develop it.

11
00:01:38,614 --> 00:01:43,682
And this equanimity has, as I say, two strands.

12
00:01:44,123 --> 00:01:50,652
It's both intellectual and attitudinal, which of course engages our emotions.

13
00:01:54,158 --> 00:02:08,318
In the Buddha's understanding, when we hold onto a view or an opinion, there are three factors involved.

14
00:02:09,562 --> 00:02:38,389
Mano and Diti and now Diti is the word for wrong understanding and the Tana is the emotional grip that we have upon our opinion and the Mano is the self or the identity we have with a particular philosophy or idea

15
00:02:40,090 --> 00:02:54,173
So now you can see this not only in religious circles, you know, fanatics, fundamentalists, but you see it just in political life, you know.

16
00:02:54,193 --> 00:03:00,864
So people identify with their opinion, with their understanding, and they label it the truth.

17
00:03:01,985 --> 00:03:03,348
I'm right, nobody else is wrong.

18
00:03:04,689 --> 00:03:06,873
Perfectly obvious to me.

19
00:03:07,512 --> 00:03:35,493
I can't understand how other people can't understand that I'm perfectly right and everybody else is wrong and in the early discourses the Buddha is constantly telling his monks and nuns not to get involved in these debates which are not about determining what is truth but about who wins and he says if you lose you go away feeling ashamed and hurt

20
00:03:36,925 --> 00:03:41,211
And if you win you're full of pride and absolutely more sure that I'm right and everybody else is wrong.

21
00:03:42,973 --> 00:03:46,778
So there's an intellectual level to this equanimity.

22
00:03:50,203 --> 00:03:59,216
The emotional level is that pain that we have when, as the Buddha points out, we're worsted in an argument.

23
00:03:59,235 --> 00:04:02,139
And the holding onto our belief systems.

24
00:04:03,622 --> 00:04:28,379
and that's all entwined around the sense of who I am so I am a socialist, I vote Labour, I'm a conservative all these I am and what it does of course, it just creates opposition just talking on political lines the fact that people align themselves to a party line

25
00:04:29,086 --> 00:04:56,680
means that you've always got this conflict going on and all the silliness of politics if people, if politicians were to think of their opinions, their views, their beliefs more in terms of a perspective you'd have a very different politic

26
00:04:57,925 --> 00:05:22,362
because a perspective, the word a perspective presumes that there are other perspectives and if you take politics to be a circle moving from left to right or right to left then you can see if it's a circle you're a dot on this circle looking at the object within whatever the problem is

27
00:05:22,934 --> 00:05:29,283
And if you see it as a perspective, you're very open to see what the person on the opposite side of the circle actually sees.

28
00:05:30,745 --> 00:05:40,740
And in this way, at least, we can formulate a more correct truth, perhaps, although you've always got to watch the majority, haven't you?

29
00:05:41,541 --> 00:05:51,237
I think it was Gandhi who said, truth can be in the majority of one or something, or truth can be...

30
00:05:52,651 --> 00:05:54,432
When he was saying, don't trust the majority.

31
00:05:58,076 --> 00:06:03,680
It's a sort of atrophying brain, you see.

32
00:06:03,701 --> 00:06:08,865
Truth can be in a minority of one, that's what he said.

33
00:06:08,884 --> 00:06:18,134
So, within ourselves, we have all these opinions, all these understandings that we've, you know, maybe we've never questioned.

34
00:06:18,213 --> 00:06:21,797
We've just believed that this is the way it is.

35
00:06:22,822 --> 00:06:24,605
You might be an eternalist.

36
00:06:25,045 --> 00:06:40,038
You might have been brought up in a religion and felt that you've been in contact with God and you're just an eternalist and that you believe there is a very caring creator who looks after us.

37
00:06:41,519 --> 00:06:51,970
On the other hand, you might have been brought up in a more secular scientific society in which everything can be reduced to atoms and subatomic particles.

38
00:06:53,418 --> 00:06:57,144
The human being is just neurons and stuff like that.

39
00:06:59,007 --> 00:07:06,038
And because you've settled into that view and we define ourselves by that view, everything we see is from that standpoint.

40
00:07:07,480 --> 00:07:13,930
And to shake it, to actually change that view is extraordinarily difficult for us.

41
00:07:17,855 --> 00:07:20,100
At least as a conscious activity.

42
00:07:20,788 --> 00:07:32,504
I mean, I'm, you know, people say, I mean, I was brought up a Catholic and people say, you know, being brought up in something like Catholicism is a real awful indoctrination and you end up completely cramped.

43
00:07:33,105 --> 00:07:34,326
I dare say some people do.

44
00:07:36,028 --> 00:07:40,415
But I'm always surprised that, you know, I woke up one morning.

45
00:07:40,935 --> 00:07:44,079
I was, I think I was 21 or 22.

46
00:07:44,312 --> 00:07:47,379
And I said to myself, I won't go to Mass this Sunday and see what happens.

47
00:07:47,858 --> 00:07:50,764
Now in those days, not to go to Mass was mortal sin.

48
00:07:51,365 --> 00:08:01,644
If you happened to die on Sunday, or on Monday morning, not having gone to Mass purposefully, well you were in for hell fire.

49
00:08:01,704 --> 00:08:06,252
It was an awful punishment for missing Mass.

50
00:08:07,836 --> 00:08:10,399
And they've repealed all that now, thank heavens.

51
00:08:13,242 --> 00:08:19,648
But I remember not going and then sort of saying to myself afterwards, well, nothing happened.

52
00:08:21,529 --> 00:08:27,355
I sort of broke through this mythical idea that if I didn't go through the Mass, something really horrible would happen.

53
00:08:28,255 --> 00:08:31,418
And nothing happened.

54
00:08:31,439 --> 00:08:34,422
And from that moment on, I never went back.

55
00:08:34,442 --> 00:08:34,581
Never.

56
00:08:34,601 --> 00:08:34,721
Never.

57
00:08:35,427 --> 00:08:37,289
Never stepped into another church.

58
00:08:37,309 --> 00:08:38,331
You know, for years and years.

59
00:08:38,371 --> 00:08:41,216
I mean, I went in afterwards for various reasons.

60
00:08:41,957 --> 00:08:43,760
But I never went back.

61
00:08:43,780 --> 00:08:47,548
And the year was 1968.

62
00:08:49,291 --> 00:08:51,355
Now, 1968 was a core year.

63
00:08:52,657 --> 00:08:54,600
There was a lovely film, a Canadian film.

64
00:08:54,941 --> 00:08:56,182
I can't remember the name of it.

65
00:08:56,202 --> 00:08:58,025
I've been racking my brains for it.

66
00:08:58,376 --> 00:09:06,471
in which it's the story of a man who, round about 60, 60 odd, this was taken a few years ago, who is dying of cancer.

67
00:09:07,272 --> 00:09:12,240
And his family, really it's a film about him dying of cancer, basically.

68
00:09:12,980 --> 00:09:20,553
But at one point, his son has come back with his girlfriend, he's working the stock markets in London,

69
00:09:21,495 --> 00:09:26,361
And the girlfriend is an art dealer.

70
00:09:27,323 --> 00:09:31,028
And she gets invited by this priest to come and see all these artifacts.

71
00:09:31,269 --> 00:09:41,881
And when she walks into the room, it's all those dreadful plaster statues that used to be all over Catholic churches and stuff.

72
00:09:41,902 --> 00:09:43,804
As art, I mean.

73
00:09:44,184 --> 00:09:46,288
As religious objects, of course, they work.

74
00:09:47,129 --> 00:09:52,041
And he wants to know how much she might consider their worth.

75
00:09:52,562 --> 00:10:01,803
And she looks at him and rather sadly says, I'm afraid, you know, you might get an individual collector who's interested, but artistically they're of no value whatsoever.

76
00:10:01,844 --> 00:10:04,490
And then he muses.

77
00:10:04,530 --> 00:10:05,592
He says, you know...

78
00:10:06,974 --> 00:10:32,761
it began in 1968 he said that the church is just emptied and that was the year of the French Revolution in Paris the great uprising students uprising so that's just a little aside but to sort of say that in my case it was an easy letting go of old

79
00:10:34,042 --> 00:10:36,945
philosophies, but then it was in the atmosphere of the time.

80
00:10:36,965 --> 00:10:42,191
And I think for most people it's quite the opposite.

81
00:10:42,491 --> 00:10:51,902
They take on quite rigid opinions, rigid views, and they find anybody else's views as simply wrong.

82
00:10:51,962 --> 00:10:58,529
I mean, I have somebody I know who simply calls all religions apart from Christianity man-made.

83
00:10:59,100 --> 00:11:01,363
the only one that's God made is Christianity.

84
00:11:02,325 --> 00:11:05,628
You know, it's a bit damning, but there we are.

85
00:11:06,990 --> 00:11:08,490
But he doesn't feel negative or anything.

86
00:11:08,551 --> 00:11:12,576
It's like, well, you know, this is the real, this is the real one, and the rest is made up.

87
00:11:17,020 --> 00:11:28,212
So all these different opinions, when you think about them, when you think of the awesome wars, I mean, the last century, of course, was really the...

88
00:11:28,902 --> 00:11:31,486
the effect of ideologies, which is exactly that.

89
00:11:32,328 --> 00:11:42,889
They're an opinion which have been lifted to the point of belief, a belief, you see, and to which people adhere, both emotionally and intellectually.

90
00:11:42,929 --> 00:11:44,413
There's an intellectual backing for it.

91
00:11:45,414 --> 00:11:49,543
And before you know it, you've got...

92
00:11:50,788 --> 00:11:52,149
You've got catastrophe on your hands.

93
00:11:52,169 --> 00:12:00,759
And that's still going on, you know, these Islamists and people like that who just can't let go of their vision.

94
00:12:00,958 --> 00:12:01,379
It's them.

95
00:12:01,879 --> 00:12:02,240
I am.

96
00:12:02,259 --> 00:12:03,181
I am.

97
00:12:06,464 --> 00:12:11,408
Now, what equanimity is asking us to do is disidentify.

98
00:12:12,070 --> 00:12:14,793
It's to see that that is a perspective.

99
00:12:15,754 --> 00:12:18,316
It's not a case of it's wrong or right.

100
00:12:18,375 --> 00:12:20,138
It's just a perspective.

101
00:12:20,674 --> 00:12:23,078
And no human being can hold the whole truth.

102
00:12:23,759 --> 00:12:24,741
It's as simple as that.

103
00:12:25,383 --> 00:12:31,212
And therefore there has to be some sort of conversation, some sort of communication.

104
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:40,168
The Buddha himself, having come to his realization

105
00:12:41,633 --> 00:12:47,447
Never went around sort of shouting, you know, I am the enlightened one.

106
00:12:47,807 --> 00:12:50,855
Actually, there's a cute little story around that which some of you might know.

107
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:57,110
He was on his way to meet his five old companions.

108
00:12:57,174 --> 00:13:07,267
And an ascetic saw him and said, you know, and was taken aback by how he looked, by the radiance of him, you know.

109
00:13:07,287 --> 00:13:10,971
And he said to him, oh, venerable, he says, you know, you look quite radiant.

110
00:13:11,052 --> 00:13:12,214
Who is your teacher, you see?

111
00:13:12,874 --> 00:13:18,201
And the Buddha goes into this enormous panegyric about, I am the fully enlightened one.

112
00:13:18,221 --> 00:13:19,081
I am the...

113
00:13:19,940 --> 00:13:21,721
I am the one who knows, and on and on you see.

114
00:13:22,442 --> 00:13:26,328
And this ascetic said, oh, there you go, yes, and then walked off.

115
00:13:26,349 --> 00:13:41,610
And I think it's funny how that little story, which is sort of funny, I mean, how he must have woken up to that's not quite the way to teach, to establish oneself as an ex-cosmic leader.

116
00:13:43,918 --> 00:13:46,865
And you do get this feeling that he had to learn how to teach.

117
00:13:47,287 --> 00:13:50,836
These things don't come with awakening.

118
00:13:51,297 --> 00:13:56,730
These are just skills which you have to teach yourself.

119
00:13:57,270 --> 00:14:01,000
So that his doctrine, if you read the scriptures, the early

120
00:14:01,705 --> 00:14:21,519
level of the scriptures you can see he's very spontaneous replies to people it's not really a fixed doctrine the idea is there it's all there but it's not into four of these ten of those one of these and all that sort of stuff that comes later the formulation of his doctrine into the four noble truths and things like that

121
00:14:24,182 --> 00:14:29,934
But his normal ploy when somebody came to him and said, you know, what's your teaching on karma or what's this or what's that?

122
00:14:30,418 --> 00:14:32,067
He was always asked, what's yours?

123
00:14:32,535 --> 00:14:36,801
He would ask them to speak their understanding.

124
00:14:36,900 --> 00:14:39,443
And then he would discuss their understanding with them.

125
00:14:40,785 --> 00:14:46,111
And of course the scriptures only record those understandings that didn't accord with his teachings.

126
00:14:46,131 --> 00:14:48,754
Otherwise it was very good, come and join me.

127
00:14:48,774 --> 00:14:49,936
It was no problem.

128
00:14:50,397 --> 00:14:55,201
But those who, the regulars who disagreed, he would then argue his point.

129
00:14:55,221 --> 00:15:02,070
And most would then be, as it were, able to let go of their hard opinion.

130
00:15:02,287 --> 00:15:04,769
You see, their stance, I'm right, you're wrong.

131
00:15:05,510 --> 00:15:12,899
And in so doing, he would then lay out his own doctrine, which they would take up.

132
00:15:14,442 --> 00:15:17,225
Not always, some didn't take it up.

133
00:15:19,668 --> 00:15:24,936
There are cases where he argues the point with somebody, but they're not convinced, and off they go.

134
00:15:27,418 --> 00:15:29,981
So there's that whole business about

135
00:15:30,855 --> 00:16:00,306
entering into the meditation entering into this experience from a position of don't know or not sure and that's always a bit frightening for us because we've always coming from a sort of stable base about I know but unfortunately those concepts those ideas those opinions even when they're right you see even when they're right become undermine your meditation

136
00:16:01,804 --> 00:16:03,769
one expects, you see.

137
00:16:04,230 --> 00:16:14,734
Now, if one has an idea, shall we say, of nibbana, so you've read the books and you've got some idea of it, so one begins to meditate with the idea of achieving nibbana,

138
00:16:15,472 --> 00:16:30,837
Now, the problem with expectation is that if you do achieve it because it's simply an expression of a concept, you'll be absolutely deluded.

139
00:16:31,818 --> 00:16:34,563
And if you don't achieve it, you're deeply disappointed.

140
00:16:36,086 --> 00:16:42,155
It's like whenever we're chasing a concept, it necessarily cramps

141
00:16:42,759 --> 00:16:45,464
the direct experience, it gets in the way.

142
00:16:46,225 --> 00:16:49,951
So we can see this in very simple things like looking at flowers.

143
00:16:51,474 --> 00:16:55,480
You know, you'll pass a shop and you'll see a flower that you recognize, roses, you see.

144
00:16:56,241 --> 00:17:03,453
And as far as we're concerned, in a sense, we've experienced that rose or that bunch of roses.

145
00:17:05,257 --> 00:17:07,079
We tend to be satisfied with that.

146
00:17:07,667 --> 00:17:09,894
There's something in it that says, oh yeah, that's roses.

147
00:17:10,295 --> 00:17:11,037
That's a green finch.

148
00:17:11,297 --> 00:17:12,240
I know a green finch.

149
00:17:13,923 --> 00:17:19,939
And it stops us looking at the rose, at the green finch, as an individual phenomena.

150
00:17:21,724 --> 00:17:47,259
and when you look at something and keep looking at it and I hope you've been experiencing this a bit and you lose that sort of definition of what it is suddenly the object brightens up as it were it takes on certain qualities that coming at it from a perception has been gently pushed aside by the mind

151
00:17:49,500 --> 00:17:50,542
And we do it with people.

152
00:17:50,723 --> 00:17:53,910
We do it most obviously when we fall in love.

153
00:17:54,491 --> 00:18:03,671
When you fall in love and there's this wonderful romantic tune going on, one sees only the beauty of the other.

154
00:18:04,231 --> 00:18:06,718
One cannot see the cracks.

155
00:18:06,877 --> 00:18:07,779
It's not possible.

156
00:18:08,906 --> 00:18:33,970
three six months at best nine months down the line thing begins to go off and well then we may find a deep relationship or we may not but the fact but the fact is that that romantic aura that that lovely surround that we put onto a person uh is in itself deluded yeah

157
00:18:34,657 --> 00:18:36,861
It's two hearts meeting, isn't it?

158
00:18:37,020 --> 00:18:40,325
Two persons meeting at that lovely level.

159
00:18:43,307 --> 00:18:58,446
So this idea of coming from a particular position of knowing, any form of knowing, must necessarily cramp the experience we're having.

160
00:18:59,106 --> 00:19:01,289
We're not fully, fully open to it.

161
00:19:02,282 --> 00:19:07,250
And one of the benefits of noting is to make that label obvious to us.

162
00:19:08,550 --> 00:19:13,657
So when you note you can see exactly what, you know, it's like a recognition of what it is.

163
00:19:14,219 --> 00:19:15,921
But that's always a halfway house.

164
00:19:17,623 --> 00:19:25,032
The point of it is to then allow that word, as it were, to recede as our attention grows upon the object.

165
00:19:27,223 --> 00:19:35,557
Until hopefully, occasionally, perhaps today, some of you have experienced just that still gaze upon something.

166
00:19:36,317 --> 00:19:41,366
A total absorption into the object, even if it's only for a small time.

167
00:19:45,153 --> 00:19:54,227
Now, when we let go of something, when we start letting go of definitions and of treasured opinions and all that,

168
00:19:54,645 --> 00:19:59,511
the heart revolts, see, it doesn't feel safe, it doesn't feel safe at all.

169
00:20:02,295 --> 00:20:06,420
And that's the fear, you see, which is based on this definition of who I am.

170
00:20:08,782 --> 00:20:20,096
So, it may be that somebody who's a theist, who believes in a personal God, you know, coming to, opening up to the fact there may not be one, is horrific.

171
00:20:21,967 --> 00:20:22,428
Isn't it?

172
00:20:22,448 --> 00:20:23,148
I mean, think about it.

173
00:20:24,191 --> 00:20:38,414
I mean, if all your life you've believed that there's this wonderful loving being who's going to greet you upon death and you open up to the possibility that there might not be one, well, it's pretty awful, isn't it?

174
00:20:38,434 --> 00:20:46,387
Much in the same way that somebody who had already settled into a nihilistic point of view, an annihilationist, rather, point of view,

175
00:20:46,789 --> 00:20:48,752
meaning that upon death everything goes away.

176
00:20:50,015 --> 00:21:09,502
The idea that in fact they might reappear, you know, in a farm shed as a cow, is something horrific, I mean, of all things, you know.

177
00:21:09,522 --> 00:21:11,025
Possibility is stunning.

178
00:21:16,472 --> 00:21:29,371
So how can we approach the Dhamma, and we're talking here about the Buddha's Dhamma, how can we approach the Dhamma in that very open-hearted, open-minded way, you see?

179
00:21:32,035 --> 00:21:34,198
That's our big problem.

180
00:21:34,939 --> 00:21:40,928
So when we begin to sit, you see, and we're beginning to investigate these three characteristics,

181
00:21:41,853 --> 00:22:11,032
it's good just before you begin to say well just for this time being I'll put aside that's easy isn't it I'll get rid of and I'll change everything I'll just put aside my understandings for a while and just see if in fact what the Buddha is talking about is true that at least opens us up to the possibility of experiencing things even when we experience things

182
00:22:11,771 --> 00:22:40,767
directly sometimes they may be wrong I mean every day we experience directly perceptually the Sun rising and then falling now we know or at least I believe that is us going around the Sun I've no proof for that my proof is that the Sun rises and the Sun sets and he's definitely going around us

183
00:22:42,366 --> 00:22:48,135
So, at the perceptual level, it doesn't mean that just because we perceive something, therefore it's right.

184
00:22:50,038 --> 00:22:55,929
And in much the same case with meditation, just because we perceive something at once, doesn't mean that's the end of it.

185
00:22:56,589 --> 00:23:04,782
One has to keep on until one is absolutely sure that, yes indeed, everything, everything arises and passes away.

186
00:23:06,266 --> 00:23:06,365
Yeah.

187
00:23:08,201 --> 00:23:14,473
that everything that I'm experiencing does not constitute anything permanent, substantial, a self.

188
00:23:14,994 --> 00:23:18,361
You have to keep seeing it, keep seeing it until you're sure of it.

189
00:23:21,125 --> 00:23:23,830
Is all desire to be banished?

190
00:23:23,851 --> 00:23:25,775
What sorts of desire are allowable?

191
00:23:25,835 --> 00:23:30,784
What sorts of desire do lead on to liberation and what sorts of desires don't?

192
00:23:30,763 --> 00:23:34,150
All these things are left up to us to discover ourselves.

193
00:23:34,471 --> 00:23:36,694
Nobody can put that in you.

194
00:23:37,115 --> 00:23:42,965
There's that very too often quoted statement that the Buddhas only point the way.

195
00:23:43,948 --> 00:23:45,329
That's all they can do.

196
00:23:45,430 --> 00:23:49,076
They can only say, look, there's the door for us to actually go through it.

197
00:23:49,984 --> 00:24:12,954
so this whole investigation is always coming from a point of not sure even when we've experienced something which we feel is absolutely right it's only when we have repeated that experience often enough for us it's like the scientific method in that sense

198
00:24:12,934 --> 00:24:32,192
